VALUES
(1, 9, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'And God blessed Noah and his sons', 0, 33, 'connection', 'Divine Blessing Theme', 'This blessing parallels God''s blessing of creation in Genesis 1:28, where He commands humanity to ''be fruitful and multiply.'' The continuity of God''s blessing demonstrates His ongoing relationship with humanity despite the flood. It emphasizes the importance of fruitfulness and stewardship in both contexts.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:28", "description": "God''s original command to humanity regarding multiplication and stewardship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Be fruitful, and multiply, and replenish the earth.', 55, 106, 'theology', 'Creation Mandate', 'Many scholars believe this command serves as a reaffirmation of the creation mandate given in Genesis 1:28. It highlights God''s desire for humanity to cultivate the earth and underscores the role of humans as caretakers of creation, reflecting God''s creative nature.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Be fruitful, and multiply', 55, 80, 'question', 'Understanding Fruitfulness', 'What does it mean for us to be ''fruitful'' in our lives today? How can we apply the command to ''multiply'' not only in physical terms but also in spiritual growth and community?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'replenish the earth.', 86, 106, 'greek', 'Replenish Meaning', 'מָלֵא (male, H4390) - to fill, to be full. This Hebrew word implies not just replacing what was lost but actively filling the earth with life and culture, reflecting God''s intention for a vibrant creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4390", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term related to ''replenish.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'the fear of you and the dread of you', 4, 40, 'theology', 'Human Authority Over Creation', 'This passage suggests that God has instituted a divine order where humans hold authority over the animal kingdom, instilling fear in creatures as a means of governance. Many scholars believe this reflects humanity''s unique role in creation as stewards tasked with care and responsibility, as echoed in Genesis 1:26-28, where humans are created in God''s image and given dominion over the earth.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:26", "description": "God''s command to humanity to have dominion over all living things."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'upon every beast of the earth', 50, 79, 'connection', 'Creation''s Subjection', 'This phrase connects with Romans 8:19-21, where Paul states that creation eagerly awaits liberation from its bondage. The fear mentioned in Genesis signifies a change in the relationship between humans and animals post-Flood. This shift underscores the gravity of sin and its impact on all of creation, highlighting the need for redemption.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 8:19", "description": "Creation''s longing for freedom from decay and bondage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'into your hand are they delivered', 186, 219, 'question', 'Responsibility of Stewardship', 'What responsibilities accompany the authority given to humanity over the creatures of the earth? How does recognizing that they are ''delivered'' into our hands shape our view of stewardship and care for the environment?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'the fear of you and the dread of you', 4, 40, 'greek', 'Hebrew Terms of Fear', 'יָרֵא (yare, H3372) - fear, terror. This term indicates a profound respect or terror that animals will have towards humanity, reflecting a hierarchical relationship established by God after the Flood.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3372", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for fear."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'Every moving thing that liveth', 0, 30, 'connection', 'Creation''s Provision', 'This phrase echoes God''s provision for creation found in Genesis 1:30, where He gives green herbs for food. The connection highlights the continuity of God''s care for humanity and His creation, suggesting a divine order where all living things are part of His sustenance plan.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:30", "description": "God''s provision of food for all living creatures"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'shall be meat for you', 31, 52, 'theology', 'Divine Permission', 'This passage suggests a significant shift in dietary laws post-flood, indicating God''s allowance of meat consumption for humanity. Many scholars believe this reflects a new phase in humanity''s relationship with creation, emphasizing stewardship and the responsibilities that accompany this authority.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'even as the green herb', 54, 76, 'greek', 'Herb and Sustenance', 'χλόη (chloē, G5528) - grass, vegetation. This term emphasizes the life-giving aspect of both plants and animals, showing a divine balance in creation where both are provided for sustenance, reflecting God''s abundant provision.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5528", "description": "Greek term for grass or vegetation"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'have I given you all things', 77, 104, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Gifts', 'What does it mean to recognize that God has given us all things? How does acknowledging this provision affect our stewardship over creation and our gratitude towards God?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'flesh with the life thereof, which is the blood thereof, shall ye not eat.', 4, 78, 'connection', 'Connection to Levitical Law', 'This prohibition against consuming blood is echoed in Leviticus 17:10-14, where God emphasizes the sanctity of blood, stating that it represents the life of the flesh. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s laws regarding dietary practices, emphasizing the value of life and the seriousness of bloodshed.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Leviticus 17:10-14", "description": "God''s command regarding the prohibition of blood consumption."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'flesh with the life thereof, which is the blood thereof', 4, 59, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Life''', 'נֶפֶשׁ (nephesh, H5315) - soul, life, living being. In Hebrew thought, blood is closely associated with the life force of a creature, indicating that consuming blood would violate the sanctity of life. This underscores the seriousness of God''s command, as it directly pertains to the essence of life itself.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5315", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'But flesh with the life thereof, which is the blood thereof, shall ye not eat.', 0, 78, 'theology', 'The Sanctity of Life', 'This passage suggests a foundational principle in biblical theology regarding the sanctity of life. Many scholars believe that this command reflects God''s concern for life, establishing a moral framework that shapes human conduct and the treatment of animals. The respect for life is pivotal in understanding God''s covenant with humanity.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'But flesh with the life thereof, which is the blood thereof, shall ye not eat.', 0, 78, 'question', 'Reflecting on Blood''s Significance', 'Why do you think God places such emphasis on the prohibition against consuming blood? How does this command shape your understanding of the value of life, both in the context of dietary laws and in broader ethical considerations?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'your blood of your lives will I require;', 11, 51, 'theology', 'Sanctity of Life', 'This passage emphasizes the sanctity of human life, suggesting that life is divinely ordained and must be treated with the utmost respect. Many scholars believe this reflects God''s concern for justice and accountability in human relationships, establishing a moral framework that values life. This principle is foundational in Christian ethics, underpinning teachings about murder and the inherent dignity of all people.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'at the hand of every beast will I require it,', 52, 97, 'connection', 'Divine Justice and Accountability', 'This phrase connects to Exodus 21:28, where the law prescribes consequences for an ox that kills a person, highlighting that all creation is under God''s authority and responsible for its actions. The requirement for blood reflects a principle of divine justice that permeates both the Old and New Testaments, underscoring God''s serious view of life and violence.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 21:28", "description": "The law concerning an ox that kills a person."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'at the hand of man; at the hand of every man’s brother', 102, 156, 'question', 'Implications of Brotherhood', 'What responsibilities do we hold towards one another, especially within the context of accountability for life? This verse suggests a communal responsibility, indicating that our actions affect not just ourselves but also our brothers and sisters. How can we foster a community that honors and protects life in light of this teaching?', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Whoso sheddeth man’s blood, by man shall his blood be shed:', 0, 59, 'theology', 'Value of Human Life', 'This passage underscores the sanctity of human life, emphasizing that murder is a serious offense against God’s creation. Many scholars believe this reflects the moral imperative that justice must be served in cases of murder, highlighting the responsibility of society to uphold life as sacred. This concept is foundational in Judeo-Christian ethics, influencing laws and moral teachings throughout history.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the theological implications of the sanctity of life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'for in the image of God made he man.', 60, 96, 'connection', 'Imago Dei Connection', 'This phrase connects directly to Genesis 1:26-27, where it states that humanity is created in the image of God. This connection is significant because it establishes the inherent dignity and worth of every person, which is a central theme in Christian anthropology. Understanding the ''image of God'' helps believers appreciate the value of each life and informs ethical discussions regarding human rights.', 'arrow.triangle.swap', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:26-27", "description": "Describes the creation of mankind in God''s image."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'by man shall his blood be shed:', 28, 59, 'question', 'Justice and Retribution', 'What does it mean for justice to be carried out by man in cases of murder? Consider how this principle informs our modern understanding of law and order. How does recognizing the seriousness of taking a life shape our responsibilities as members of a community committed to justice?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'for in the image of God made he man.', 60, 96, 'greek', 'Image of God', 'צֶלֶם (tselem, H6754) - image, likeness. This Hebrew term emphasizes that humans reflect God''s character and essence, which is foundational for understanding human dignity and purpose. It establishes the profound relationship between God and humanity, suggesting that every person''s life is to be valued and protected.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6754", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''image''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'be ye fruitful, and multiply;', 9, 38, 'connection', 'Creation Mandate', 'This phrase echoes God''s command in Genesis 1:28 where He instructs humanity to ''be fruitful and multiply, and fill the earth.'' This connection highlights the continuity of God''s intention for humanity to grow and thrive, emphasizing the importance of procreation and stewardship over creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:28", "description": "God''s original command to humanity regarding growth and stewardship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'bring forth abundantly in the earth,', 39, 75, 'theology', 'Theological Significance of Multiplication', 'Many scholars believe this command reflects God''s desire for humanity to participate in His creative work. The call to ''bring forth abundantly'' signifies not only physical reproduction but also a spiritual mandate to cultivate life, community, and faithfulness in our environment, aligning with the overarching theme of covenant relationships throughout Scripture.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'multiply therein.', 80, 97, 'question', 'Reflection on Multiplication', 'What does it mean to multiply in the context of our lives today? How can we apply the principle of abundance to our relationships, communities, and spiritual lives, ensuring that we reflect God''s creativity and generosity in our actions?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'be ye fruitful, and multiply;', 9, 38, 'greek', 'Original Language Insight', 'The Hebrew phrase for ''be ye fruitful'' is פרה (parah, H6509) - to bear fruit, to be fruitful. This term emphasizes the active participation of the individual in the process of growth and productivity, underscoring the responsibility placed upon humanity in fulfilling God''s command.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6509", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term relating to fruitfulness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'And God spake unto Noah, and to his sons with him, saying,', 0, 58, 'connection', 'Divine Communication', 'This moment parallels God''s communication with Abraham in Genesis 12:1, where God speaks directly to an individual to initiate a covenant. Such direct communication highlights God''s desire for relationship and guidance with humanity, showcasing His initiative in establishing His plans.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:1", "description": "God''s call to Abraham marks another pivotal moment of divine instruction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'And God spake unto Noah, and to his sons with him, saying,', 0, 58, 'theology', 'Covenantal Theology', 'This verse marks the establishment of a covenant, a central theme in biblical theology. Many scholars believe this indicates God''s commitment not only to Noah but to all creation, signifying a new beginning after the flood. The covenant reflects God''s grace and mercy, emphasizing His desire to maintain a relationship with humanity.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Waltke, Bruce K. ''Genesis: A Commentaries on Genesis 1-15.''", "description": "This commentary discusses the significance of God''s covenants throughout Genesis."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'And God spake unto Noah, and to his sons with him, saying,', 0, 58, 'question', 'Listening for God''s Voice', 'What does it mean for us today that God spoke directly to Noah and his sons? How can we discern God''s voice amidst our daily lives, and are we attentive to His guidance as Noah was?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'And God spake unto Noah, and to his sons with him, saying,', 0, 58, 'greek', 'Word of God', 'דבר (dabar, H1696) - to speak, declare, command. This Hebrew term underscores the authority and intentionality behind God''s words, emphasizing their power to shape reality and establish covenantal relationships.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1696", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used for ''spake''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'I establish my covenant with you', 15, 47, 'connection', 'Covenant Theme in Scripture', 'This phrase connects to the broader theme of covenant throughout Scripture, particularly in Genesis 17:7 where God reaffirms His covenant with Abraham. Understanding this link highlights the continuity of God''s promises to His people across generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 17:7", "description": "God''s covenant with Abraham, showing the ongoing nature of divine promises."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'my covenant with you', 27, 47, 'theology', 'God''s Unconditional Promises', 'This passage suggests that God''s covenants are unconditional. Many scholars believe that this reflects God''s steadfast love and commitment to humanity despite human failings, which is a cornerstone of biblical theology regarding divine grace.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'with your seed after you', 53, 77, 'question', 'Generational Impact of Covenants', 'How does the idea of God''s covenant extending to ''your seed after you'' challenge or encourage your understanding of spiritual legacy within your family or community?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'I, behold, I establish', 4, 26, 'greek', 'Key Hebrew Terms', 'אֲנִי (ani, H589) - I; אֵן (hen, H188) - behold. These words emphasize God''s personal involvement and the importance of the covenant, inviting attention to His divine action.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H589", "description": "Strong''s number for ''I''."}, {"type": "strongs", "reference": "H188", "description": "Strong''s number for ''behold''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'And with every living creature that is with you,', 0, 48, 'connection', 'Covenant with Creation', 'This phrase highlights God''s inclusive covenant not only with humanity but also with all living creatures. Similar themes are found in Isaiah 11:6-9, where the peaceable kingdom includes animals. This connection emphasizes God''s care for all creation, reflecting His desire for harmony and stewardship.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Isaiah 11:6-9", "description": "Vision of peace among all creatures"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'of the fowl, of the cattle, and of every beast of the earth', 49, 108, 'theology', 'Universal Covenant', 'The mention of various categories of animals signifies the breadth of God''s covenant. Many scholars believe this reflects a foundational principle of stewardship and care for creation, which is integral to God''s design. It underscores that God''s grace extends beyond humanity to all living beings.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'every living creature that is with you', 9, 47, 'question', 'Understanding God''s Inclusivity', 'What does it mean for us today that God includes ''every living creature'' in His covenant? How can this understanding of divine inclusivity influence our treatment of animals and the environment?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'And I will establish my covenant with you;', 0, 42, 'theology', 'Covenant Theology', 'This passage highlights the significance of God''s covenant relationship with humanity. Covenants are foundational to biblical theology, representing commitments between God and His people. Many scholars believe this particular covenant signifies a shift from judgment to grace, as it promises that God will not destroy the earth again by flood, demonstrating His mercy and faithfulness. This underscores the theme of redemption that recurs throughout Scripture.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Waltke, Bruce K. Genesis: A Commentary.", "description": "Provides insight into the covenantal framework in Genesis."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'neither shall all flesh be cut off any more by the waters of a flood;', 43, 112, 'connection', 'Judgment and Mercy', 'This phrase connects with 2 Peter 3:6-7, where the flood is mentioned as a historical event that serves as a warning against future judgment. Understanding this connection emphasizes that God''s promise of mercy does not negate His justice; rather, it reveals a balance between divine judgment and grace. It reassures believers of God’s commitment to preserving life and His creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "2 Peter 3:6-7", "description": "References the flood as a past judgment."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'neither shall there any more be a flood to destroy the earth.', 113, 174, 'question', 'Reflecting on God''s Promises', 'What does it mean for us today that God promises never to destroy the earth with a flood again? How should this assurance shape our understanding of His character and our relationship with creation? Reflecting on this promise invites us to consider our stewardship of the earth and the hope we have in God''s faithfulness amidst uncertainty.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'And I will establish my covenant with you;', 0, 42, 'greek', 'Covenant Understanding', 'בְּרִית (berith, H1285) - covenant, treaty, alliance. This Hebrew term encapsulates the foundational concept of a covenant in Scripture, indicating a solemn agreement that carries obligations and promises. The use of this term here underscores the seriousness and commitment involved in God''s relationship with humanity.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1285", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word ''covenant''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'This is the token of the covenant', 14, 47, 'connection', 'Covenant Theme', 'This phrase connects to Exodus 34:10, where God establishes a covenant with Israel, proclaiming His wonders. Both passages highlight God''s commitment to His people and creation. Understanding this connection helps emphasize the continuity of God''s promises throughout Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 34:10", "description": "Another instance of God establishing a covenant."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'covenant which I make between me and you', 39, 79, 'theology', 'Covenant Theology', 'This passage underscores the significance of divine covenants in biblical theology. Many scholars believe that God''s covenants reflect His relational nature and commitment to humanity. The covenant with Noah signifies a universal promise, extending beyond Israel and emphasizing God''s mercy.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'for perpetual generations', 124, 149, 'question', 'Understanding Perpetuity', 'What does ''perpetual generations'' imply about God''s faithfulness across time? How does this assurance influence our understanding of His promises today and shape our expectations for the future?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'every living creature that is with you', 84, 122, 'greek', 'Significant Terms', 'נֶפֶשׁ (nephesh, H5315) - soul, life, creature. This term emphasizes the life aspect of all living beings, underscoring God''s covenant not only with humanity but with all creation, reflecting His care for the entire ecosystem.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5315", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'I do set my bow in the cloud', 0, 28, 'connection', 'Covenant Symbols', 'This phrase connects to Ezekiel 1:28, where the glory of the Lord is likened to a rainbow. Both instances highlight God''s presence and promise. The rainbow serves as a visible reminder of God''s faithfulness in both texts, reinforcing the idea that God uses creation to communicate His promises.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ezekiel 1:28", "description": "Ezekiel''s vision of God''s glory parallels the significance of the rainbow as a covenant sign."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'and it shall be for a token of a covenant', 30, 71, 'theology', 'Covenant Theology', 'Many scholars believe this verse establishes the foundational concept of covenant in Scripture, representing God''s unbreakable promise to humanity. The rainbow signifies not just a promise but also a relationship characterized by grace and mercy, which is central to biblical theology.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Waltke, Bruce K. ''Genesis: A Commentary.''", "description": "Discusses the significance of the covenant in the narrative of Genesis."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'my bow in the cloud', 9, 28, 'greek', 'Significance of ''bow''', 'קֶשֶׁת (qeshet, H7198) - bow, rainbow. In Hebrew, this word signifies both a weapon and a symbol of peace. Here, it serves as a reminder of God''s mercy after judgment, indicating a shift from destruction to promise.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7198", "description": "Strong''s number for ''bow,'' emphasizing its dual significance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 9, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'between me and the earth', 72, 96, 'question', 'Understanding God''s Promise', 'What does it mean for God to make a covenant not only with Noah but also with all of creation? How does this broaden our understanding of God''s relationship with the world and His ongoing commitment to it?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');